#Plotting the feather wavelengths, also looking at the effect of the backgrounds used

def plot_spect_df(df):
    for sample, index in zip(df.values,df.index):
        if index.split('_')[1] == 'B':
            c = 'grey'
        else:
            c = 'white'
        plt.plot(df.columns, sample, color=c)
    plt.title("Spectral composition")
    plt.xlabel("Wavelength (nm)")
    plt.ylabel("Reflection")
    white_patch = mpatches.Patch(color='white', label='White background')
    black_patch = mpatches.Patch(color='grey', label='Black background')
    plt.legend(handles=[white_patch,black_patch])
    plt.show()

plot_spect_df(nir_df.iloc[:,:-1])

As seen in the plot, the strengths of the signals is quite different between the samples. It is quite clear that the white background reflect light better than black background. Some normalization needs to be done before extracting more spectral information from the data.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

mms = MinMaxScaler(feature_range=(0,1))
stc = StandardScaler()

nir_norm_val = nir_df.iloc[:,:-1]
# Only use the NIR wavelengths 700- 2100
nir_norm_val = nir_norm_val.drop(columns=[column for column in nir_norm_val.columns if column < 700])
# Normalizing the spectrals (wavelength/sum(wavelengths))
nir_norm_val = nir_norm_val.subtract(nir_norm_val.mean(axis=1),axis=0)
nir_norm_val.iloc[:,:] = mms.fit_transform(nir_norm_val)# every value minimum of 0 maximum of 1
nir_norm_val.iloc[:,:] = stc.fit_transform(nir_norm_val)# every value average of 0 and stdev of 1

There is a clear separation between two groups, probably between lighter and darker feathers The approach will be spectral decomposition by PCA.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from matplotlib import colormaps as cm

color_dict = {'W':'white','B':'grey',
              'G':'silver', 'I':'indigo'}


data = nir_norm_val
colors = nir_df["Colour"].values


pca = PCA()
pca.fit(data)

pca.explained_variance_ratio_[:5]

PC1 = pca.fit_transform(data)[:,0]
PC2 = pca.fit_transform(data)[:,1]


fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(14, 9))
for c,p1,p2 in zip(colors,PC1,PC2):
    col = color_dict[c]
    ax.scatter(p1, p2, color=col)
white_patch = mpatches.Patch(color='white', label='White feather')
black_patch = mpatches.Patch(color='grey', label='Black feather')
grey_patch = mpatches.Patch(color='silver', label='Grey feather')
purple_patch = mpatches.Patch(color='indigo', label='Purple iridescent feather')
ax.set_xlabel(f'PC1({pca.explained_variance_ratio_[0]*100:.3}%)', fontsize=14)
ax.set_ylabel(f'PC2({pca.explained_variance_ratio_[1]*100:.3}%)', fontsize=14)
ax.set_title('PCA', fontsize=20)
ax.legend(handles=[white_patch,black_patch,grey_patch,purple_patch])

plt.show()

As seen above in the PCA, one can clearly distinguish the near-infrared reflectance spectrum of white feathers compared to darker feathers. But there is also an interesting seperation between the two darker feather groups, with PCR it is possible to use PCA in combination with regression to regress features from the Excel with the first principle component as that explains the highest difference between the groups.

In the data we have length father, length mother and eiher male or female. The best option for correlating these factors to the offspring's height will be: Multi-Linear Regression (MLR).

In [ ]:
from sklearn import linear_model

x = gal_df[['father','mother','male','female']]
y = gal_df['height']


# with sklearn
regr = linear_model.LinearRegression()
regr.fit(x, y)
score = regr.score(x,y)

print(f'constant:{regr.intercept_}\ncoeff:{regr.coef_}\naccuracy:{score*100:.03}%')

constant:17.95773567408137
coeff:[ 0.40597803  0.32149514  2.61297566 -2.61297566]
accuracy:64.0%

which means for offspring: ~y = 17.9577 + 0.40597803* h_father + 0.3215* h_mother + 2.613* is_male + -2.613* is_female

In [ ]:
def f(var_list):
    father = var_list[0]
    mother = var_list[1]
    male = var_list[2]
    female = var_list[3]
    const = 17.95773567408137
    y = father*0.40597803+mother*0.32149514+male*2.61297566+female*-2.61297566 + const 
    return y

gal_df["estimated_height"] = [f(i) for i in x.values]
